  "doc_id": "43977",
  "text": "Median nerve entrapment can occur around the elbow joint. The most common site of median nerve compression at the elbow level is between the two heads of the pronator teres muscle [CITATION_1] . The patients having median nerve compression at this level may have pain and numbness in the volar side of the elbow and forearm. The hand symptoms may be similar to those in the case of carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS). This is called pronator teres syndrome. The causes of pronator teres syndrome may relate to trauma with hematoma, pronator teres muscle hypertrophy, or congenital abnormalities [CITATION_2] . The demonstration of the causes of the pronator teres syndrome by US may be possible if there is a mass or hematoma causing compression of the median nerve. However, in the absence of such findings, it may not be easy to make a diagnosis or to find the cause of nerve compression with US, since the fibrous bands or scar tissue may be too small to visualize with US [CITATION_3] . MRI can demonstrate the denervation muscle signal changes and determine the level of nerve compression [CITATION_4] .",
